🧠 Why Docker in Microservices?

In microservices:

You have multiple small services
Each service may need:
Different Java versions
Different configs
Different dependencies

👉 Docker solves this by:
➡️ Running each service in its own isolated container
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🧠 Real-Time Scenario (Very Important for L2)
🏢 E-commerce Application

You have:

Order Service (Java 17)
Payment Service (Java 11)
Inventory Service (Node.js)
Notification Service (Python)

❌ Without Docker:

Install all runtimes manually
Version conflicts
Works on dev, fails in prod 😓

✅ With Docker:

Each service has its own container:
Order → Docker container with Java 17
Payment → Docker container with Java 11
Inventory → Node container
All run independently without conflicts
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
❓ Why not use Docker alone?

👉 Docker runs containers, but:

No auto-scaling
No self-healing
No load balancing

➡️ Kubernetes handles all this

🚀 Simple Analogy (Easy to remember)
Docker = Pack food into boxes
Kubernetes = Manage delivery of those boxes at scale
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
❓ What happens if a container crashes?
👉 Kubernetes automatically restarts it (self-healing)
