“I worked on a banking migration project where we moved a monolithic system to Spring Boot-based microservices.

The architecture includes an API Gateway for routing, Eureka as service registry, and multiple services like Publisher and Subscriber services.

The request flow starts from the client hitting the API Gateway, which routes to the appropriate microservice. For synchronous communication,
we used REST APIs, and for asynchronous communication, we used Kafka, especially for event-driven flows like transaction processing.

We implemented the Saga pattern to handle distributed transactions across services.

For CI/CD, we used Jenkins to build and deploy applications. Each service was containerized using Docker and deployed on Kubernetes for scalability and fault tolerance.

For logging, we used SLF4J and monitored logs using the ELK stack for debugging and production monitoring.

My role involved developing REST APIs, integrating Kafka consumers/producers, and handling production issues using logs and monitoring tools.”
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


“We used Kafka for asynchronous communication when a request didn’t need an immediate response.

For example, in the banking migration project, when a transaction was created in the Publisher service,
we didn’t want the user to wait for downstream services like notification or ledger updates. So the Publisher service produced a Kafka message to a topic transaction-events. The Subscriber service consumed the message asynchronously and processed the ledger entry and notification.

This solved latency issues and decoupled services. If a consumer was down,
Kafka retained messages until it was back, ensuring reliability. For fast-response requirements, like checking account balance, we used synchronous REST APIs.”
